Question 1 — Enzyme Inhibition & Lipase
1.1 — Describe how a non-competitive inhibitor reduces the rate of an enzyme-controlled reaction (3 marks)
Mark scheme:

Attaches to the enzyme at a site other than the active site (accept allosteric/inhibitor site)
Changes the shape of the active site (or changes the tertiary structure of the enzyme)
Active site and substrate no longer complementary → less/no enzyme-substrate complexes form
1.2 — Use Figure 1 to explain why pectin is a non-competitive inhibitor (1 mark)
Figure 1 shows that increasing substrate/lipid concentration does not increase the rate when inhibitor is present.

Mark scheme:

With inhibitor, increasing substrate concentration does not increase/affect rate of reaction
OR high substrate concentration does not overcome the inhibition
OR high substrate concentration does not reach the maximum rate
