Question 3 — Biodiversity & Farming
3.1 — What data needed to calculate index of diversity? (1 mark)
Mark scheme: Number of species and number of individuals in each species (accept "population/abundance of each species"; ignore frequency)

3.2 — Two ways to ensure index of diversity is representative (2 marks)
Mark scheme:

Random samples
Large number of samples (accept ≥10 if specified) / continue sampling until stable running mean
3.3 — Why does biodiversity decrease with larger fields? (1 mark)
Modern farming → larger fields, removal of hedges.

Mark scheme: Larger fields have relatively more centre / less edge / less hedge / fewer species

3.4 — One advantage and one disadvantage of replanting hedges (2 marks)
Mark scheme:

Advantage: Greater biodiversity → increase in predators of pests (less pesticide/more yield) / increase in pollinators (more yield) / may attract subsidies/tourists
Disadvantage: Reduced land area for crop growth / greater biodiversity may increase pest population / increased interspecific competition / more difficult to farm (e.g. can't use large machinery)
