Question 10 — Extended Response (Properties of Water, Biochemical Tests, Polymers)
10.1 — Explain five properties that make water important for organisms (5 marks, max 5 from list)
Mark scheme:

A metabolite in condensation / hydrolysis / photosynthesis / respiration
A solvent → metabolic reactions can occur / transport of substances
High heat capacity → buffers changes in temperature
Large latent heat of vaporisation → cooling effect through evaporation
Cohesion (H bonding) → supports columns of water in plants (transpiration stream)
Cohesion → produces surface tension supporting small organisms
Also accept: ice floating maintains aquatic habitat; transparency allows light for photosynthesis.

10.2 — Biochemical tests for lipid, non-reducing sugar, and amylase (5 marks, max 4 if only 2 tests attempted)
Mark scheme:

Lipid:

Add ethanol, shake/mix, then add water (OR add Sudan III and mix) — reject heating
White/milky emulsion (OR red layer for Sudan III) — reject precipitate
Non-reducing sugar: 3. Benedict's test → stays blue (negative) 4. Boil with acid, then neutralise with alkali 5. Heat with Benedict's → becomes red/orange precipitate (dependent on attempting step 4; must state heating again)

Amylase: 6. Add biuret reagent → becomes purple/violet/mauve/lilac — reject heating 7. Add starch, leave, then test for reducing sugar / absence of starch

10.3 — Condensation & hydrolysis reactions; two examples of polymers and monomers (5 marks)
Mark scheme:

Condensation joins monomers together, forms a bond, and releases water
Hydrolysis breaks a bond between monomers and uses water
Example 1 — e.g. amino acids → polypeptide/protein; nucleotides → DNA/RNA; α-glucose → starch/glycogen; β-glucose → cellulose
Example 2 — a different valid example from above
Reference to a correct bond within a named polymer (e.g. peptide bond in polypeptide, glycosidic bond in starch; reject "ester bond")
Polymers must contain many monomers. Reject triglycerides (once).

